post_cb({"18944775": {"ParentId": "18944751", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Memory_leak\" rel=\"nofollow\">Memory leak</a> are caused by dynamic memory allocation.</p>\n<p>There is no dynamic allocation here, so <strong>no memory leak</strong>.</p>\n<p>Actually, <em>string literals</em> have <em>static storage duration</em>. The standard says (draft n3690):</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_18944751_18944775_0\"><strong>3.7.1 Static storage duration [basic.stc.static]</strong></p>\n<p id=\"so_18944751_18944775_1\">All variables which do not have dynamic storage duration, do not have thread storage duration, and are not local have static storage duration. <strong>The storage for these entities shall last for the duration of the program</strong>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "OwnerUserId": "1394283", "LastEditorUserId": "1394283", "LastEditDate": "2013-09-22T14:27:30.937", "Id": "18944775", "Score": "3", "CreationDate": "2013-09-22T14:17:07.753", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-22T14:27:30.937"}, "18944751": {"CommentCount": "8", "ViewCount": "276", "CreationDate": "2013-09-22T14:14:33.163", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-22T14:27:30.937", "Title": "Can reassigning a C style string cause a memory leak?", "AcceptedAnswerId": "18944774", "PostTypeId": "1", "Id": "18944751", "Score": "3", "Body": "<p>Can reassigning a C style string cause a memory leak? Like so:</p>\n<pre><code>char * s = \"Hello!\";\ns = \"Hello, world!\";\n</code></pre>\n<p>My question may appear as stupid, but please bear with me; I am currently still a dummie in C++.</p>\n<p>In the second line of code, the C style string <code>s</code> is longer, so does it have it internally reallocate memory? Does this cause a memory leak? And do I have to call <code>delete</code>?</p>\n<p>Thanks</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><c><string>", "OwnerUserId": "1403986", "AnswerCount": "3"}, "18944774": {"ParentId": "18944751", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "1", "Body": "<p>Actually, technically no.  String literals are provided special static allocation.  See</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/349025/is-a-string-literal-in-c-created-in-static-memory\">Is a string literal in c++ created in static memory?</a></p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "2129919", "LastEditorUserId": "-1", "LastEditDate": "2017-05-23T10:31:56.380", "Id": "18944774", "Score": "4", "CreationDate": "2013-09-22T14:17:00.423", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-22T14:17:00.423"}, "18944761": {"ParentId": "18944751", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>There is no dynamic memory allocation so there is no leak. What you have is a pointer pointing to a string literal which is stored somewhere in implementation defined read only memory.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "452307", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "18944761", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2013-09-22T14:15:46.743", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-22T14:15:46.743"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_18944751_18944775_1": {"section_id": 7164, "quality": 0.9, "length": 18}}, "n3337": {"so_18944751_18944775_1": {"section_id": 6908, "quality": 0.9, "length": 18}}, "n4659": {"so_18944751_18944775_1": {"section_id": 8672, "quality": 0.9, "length": 18}}}});